Stopping Distances
That the stopping distance of a vehicle is the distance covered between the driver spotting a hazard
and the vehicle coming to a stop. It is the sum of the thinking distance and braking distance.
That thinking distance is the distance the vehicle travels during the driver’s reaction time.
That braking distance is the distance travelled whilst the vehicle’s brakes are applied.
That the thinking distance is affected by the speed of the vehicle and the driver’s reaction time.
That a driver’s reaction time is affected by factors including tiredness, drugs and distractions.
That the braking distance is affected by the speed and mass of the vehicle, how good the vehicle’s
brakes are, how good the grip is between the vehicle and the road (because of the condition of the
tyres and the state of the road).
